comment.body:
See the first task on the PR description.

There I wrote about that issue. Since the value itself isn't deterministic here, we need to pass the decisions made in `Helpers.calcTotal` into the `ModifiableValue` data so template know what actually happend and not just what methods were used, due to that false positive case.

Personally I don't think it's to bad and I could live with less complexity, however introducing such a decision indicator would be more explicit; which I like.

So, I'd suggest we use a simple union string type (enums in TS are a bit iffy in practice), matching the method used: 'sum', 'override', 'upgrade', 'deprecate', matching the other data structures. And on templates just check against that (in JS as to benefit from typing).

pull_request.title: [Feature] Improve system handling of ADD, UPGRDE and DOWNGRADE modes when addressing a ModifiableValue field or its properties
pull_request.body: This will alter effect change modes when the add mode is applied to a ModifiableField, either direct or indirect. I don't see a use case for Add on those fields, and even if only .base would be a good idea. So just apply Add as modify on those. Changes made in this PR to previous behavior: - [Feature] Add mode works like Modify mode. When addressing a value (attribute, skill, limit) it will apply the change value to the modify chain. For that the change key can either directly address the value (`system.attributes.body`) or indirectly with any of its properties used for calculation (`system.attributes.body.value`, `.base`, `.mod`, `.temp`). - [Feature] Upgrade and Downgrade modes now support a value with the same addressing rules as described. Both only apply to the overall total, not the base rating. Upgrade applied and used: Upgrade application applied but unused: Downgrade applied and used: ## Possible improvements - [ ] ModifiableValue template helpers can't differentiate if a total value is the sum or an upgraded / downgraded value. This will show on the sheets as upgrade applied even though the un-upgraded total would be the same. This could be resolved by introducing a new ModifiableField field: 'totalMode' with choices 'sum', 'override', 'upgrade', 'downgrade' to determine how a total value has been calculated. - [x] Skills use `SR5ActiveEffect._applyLegacy` instead of `ModifiableField.applyChange` due to how Foundry seems to work with `TypedObjectField` and `actor.system.schema.getField('skills.active.automatics')` - [ ] Allow upgrade / downgrade to address the base rating. To avoid issues with base value display vs actualy value (see system modifiers under Misc tab), and for increased transparency, we're likely better of by introducing a `.override.target` with choices 'rating', 'total'. To avoid having another data point on effects, we could set this based on the change key (`body.base` => target = 'rating', anything else => target = 'total') - [x] Check all modes for sheet breaking when applied to a ModifiableValue field

issue.title: Management Framework Cluster::listen_websocket() needs to support TLS and different broker data format is returned
issue.body:
Recently, scripts/policy/frameworks/management/controller/main.zeek was switched from Broker::listen_websocket() to Cluster::listen_websocket() which was not configured to use TLS.

That resulted in zeek-client be unable to connect when TLS Is required:
```
zeek@zeek-test1:~$ zeek-client get-nodes
error: socket TLS error in connect() with controller zeek-test1.es.net:2149: [SSL: SSLV3_ALERT_HANDSHAKE_FAILURE] sslv3 alert handshake failure (_ssl.c:1007)
```

(Also see https://cirrus-ci.com/task/4737400997412864)

This appears to be partially fixed by doing something like this:

```
        if ( cni$bound_port != 0/unknown )
                {
                local tls_options = Cluster::WebSocketTLSOptions(
                        $cert_file=Broker::ssl_certificate,
                        $key_file=Broker::ssl_keyfile,
                        $ca_file="NONE",
                        $ciphers="AECDH-AES256-SHA@SECLEVEL=0:AECDH-AES256-SHA:P-384",
                );
                local ws_opts = Cluster::WebSocketServerOptions($listen_addr=to_addr(cni$address),
                                                                $listen_port=cni$bound_port,
                                                                $tls_options=tls_options);
                Cluster::listen_websocket(ws_opts);
                websocket_info = fmt("websocket port %s:%s", cni$address, cni$bound_port);
                }
```

That solves the TLS connection problem, however, it seems like the Cluster websocket is also returning a different data format.

```
$ zeek-client -vvv get-nodes
info: connecting to controller zeek-test1.es.net:2149
info: peered with controller zeek-test1.es.net:2149
debug: received event "Management::Controller::API::get_nodes_response"
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/local/zeek/bin/zeek-client", line 68, in <module>
    sys.exit(main())
  File "/usr/local/zeek/bin/zeek-client", line 62, in main
    return args.run_cmd(args)
  File "/usr/local/zeek/versions/63574b9fd4645a2f21d7ba3388e16c1b4c55812d/lib/zeek/python/zeekclient/cli.py", line 565, in cmd_get_nodes
    nstats = [NodeStatus.from_brokertype(nstat_data) for nstat_data in res.data]
  File "/usr/local/zeek/versions/63574b9fd4645a2f21d7ba3388e16c1b4c55812d/lib/zeek/python/zeekclient/cli.py", line 565, in <listcomp>
    nstats = [NodeStatus.from_brokertype(nstat_data) for nstat_data in res.data]
  File "/usr/local/zeek/versions/63574b9fd4645a2f21d7ba3388e16c1b4c55812d/lib/zeek/python/zeekclient/types.py", line 835, in from_brokertype
    port = data[5].to_py()
  File "/usr/local/zeek/versions/63574b9fd4645a2f21d7ba3388e16c1b4c55812d/lib/zeek/python/zeekclient/brokertypes.py", line 657, in __getitem__
    return self._elements[idx]
IndexError: list index out of range
```

Adding a print(data) to lib/zeek/python/zeekclient/types.py:

    834     def from_brokertype(cls, data):
    835         print(data)
    836         port = data[5].to_py()

We can see that the data format from the websocket is different.  (I'll attach full copies, data.json being the 'new' version)

It has gone from:

```
{
    "@data-type": "vector",
    "data": [
        {
            "@data-type": "string",
            "data": "agent-zeek-test1.es.net"
        },
        {
            "@data-type": "enum-value",
            "data": "Management::RUNNING"
        },
        {
            "@data-type": "enum-value",
            "data": "Management::AGENT"
        },
        {
            "@data-type": "enum-value",
            "data": "Supervisor::NONE"
        },
        {

```
To:
```

{
    "@data-type": "vector",
    "data": [
        {
            "@data-type": "string",
            "data": "zeek::Broker::detail::DataVal"
        },
        {
            "@data-type": "vector",
            "data": [
                {
                    "@data-type": "vector",
                    "data": [
                        {
                            "@data-type": "string",
                            "data": "test1-w2"
                        },
                        {
                            "@data-type": "enum-value",
                            "data": "Management::PENDING"

```

issue.title: Suggestion: Lung collapse should be caused by perforating wounds
issue.body: The title is pretty self explanatory, gunshots and stab wounds should probably cause lung collapse

comment.body:
There is a lung collapse, but Its only triggered by strong explosions. 

Im not an author of the mod, and whatever I write below is IMHO, but judging from my experience in previous version of the game, obscuring bullet/slash wounds to the chest as bleeding wounds is the best decision for the gameplay purposes. There is enough on the plate already in this mod, and with new update there is even more to carry about without constantly collapsing wounds. 

Torso is the most targeted part in the combat with lungs being a subpart of it would make lung collapses just from bullets a pretty annoying affair to deal with. There are conditions coming from that require advanced research to deal with, which would make tribe/medieval playthrough pretty much impossible. Of course it possible to make chances just very small, but at that point it might not even exist, its better to save on performance than having to roll each and every chest wound for lung collapse. Explosive weapons come pretty late anyway, where colony should be having methods to deal with lung collapses. 

Thats my vision of it, at least, and I understand why it works that way.

broker/Data: Support unwrapping Broker::Data records

Calling val_to_data() on a Broker::Data ends up wrapping the
Broker::Data record instead of using the contained broker::value
directly.

Seems this should be the default behavior and wonder if the flag
even makes sense, but for a 8.0 backport that seems more reasonable.

also be Broker::Data values. I'm not super sure about the validity of
the test, because it's essentially demonstrating any-nesting, but
it's not leading to extra Broker::Data encoding.
